        "arabicBrief": " وصل عدد المرشحين والمرشحات للإنتخابات النيابية 2022 إلى 1,043 مرشح ومرشحة بزيادة نسبة 6.8% عن العام 2018 (976 مرشحاً ومرشحة). ",
        "description": "The number of female and male candidates for the parliamentary elections of 2022 has reached 1,043 female and male candidates, an increase of 6.8% over the number of candidates of 2018 election (976 male and female candidates).Upon analysing the numbers of female and male candidates, it became evident that these numbers have witnessed an increase in all major electoral districts except for three: Tripoli - Miniyeh - Denniyeh (3 fewer candidates), Akkar (5 fewer candidates), and Nabatieh - Bint Jbeil - Marjeyoun - Hasbaya (20 fewer candidates). North III electoral district is the largest district witnessing the highest increase in the number of both male and female candidates (Batroun, Koura, Bsharri and Zgharta).Each of the following districts witnessed the candidacy of&nbsp; more than 100 candidates: Chouf and Aley (100 nominations for 13 seats), Beirut II (118 nominations for 11 seats), Tripoli and Miniyeh - Denniyeh (141 nominations for 11 seats). When calculating the ratio of the number of candidates to the number of seats in the major electoral districts, it appeared that: all major electoral districts witnessed the registration of approximately 7 candidates and above for each seat (the highest of which is Akkar with 12 candidates for each seat), with the exception of two electoral districts; South II and South III, only witnessing 3.5 candidacy for each seaUpon reviewing the electoral sub-districts for further analysis, it became clear that each of the following electoral sub-districts has witnessed a decrease in candidacy compared to 2018:</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">-2 in Nabatieh</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">-6 in Bint jbeil&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">-12 in Marjeyoun and Hasbaya</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">-5 in Akkar&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">-12 in Miniyeh - Denniyeh (adjusted by an increase of candidacy in Tripoli)&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">-1 in Bsharri&nbsp;</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">As for the electoral sub-districts that witnessed a significant increase in the number of candidates compared to the 2018 election:</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">+9 in Zahle</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">+10 in Saida</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">+9 in Tripoli</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">+8 in Beirut I</span></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">+9 in Metn</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The following electoral sub-districts recorded the highest competition, with more than 10 candidates running for each seat: Zahle (72 candidates for 7 seats), Akkar (84 candidates for 7 seats), Tripoli (107 candidates for 8 seats), Beirut II (118 candidates for 11 seats), and Jbeil (31 candidates for 3 seats). Whereas the competition is mild in the following electoral sub-districts: Tyre (14 candidates for 4 seats), and Bint Jbeil (9 candidates for 3 seats).</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The following are the sectarian seats witnessing the highest number of candidacy:</span></p><ul><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The sole seat for Maronites in West Bekaa and Rachaya (15 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The sole seat for Catholics in Baalbek - Hermel (10 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The two seats for Sunnis in Baalbek - Hermel (21 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The three seats for Sunnis in Akkar (43 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The sole seat for Alawites in Akkar (16 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The three seats for Sunnis in Miniyeh - Denniyeh (34 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The five seats for Sunnis in Tripoli (62 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The sole seat for Alawites in Tripoli (19 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The sole seat for Maronites in Tripoli (18 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The sole seat for minorities in Beirut I (15 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The sole seat for Evangelists in Beirut II (112 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The sole seat for Druze in Beirut II (12 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The six seats for Sunnis in Beirut I (69 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">The sole seat for shiites in jbeil (12 candidates)</span></li></ul><p><br></p><p><span style=\"background-color: transparent; color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">As for the percentage of difference in candidacy between the 2018 and 2022 elections, several alterations were recorded, including:</span></p><ul><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">An increase by 66 % in candidacy for the Orthodox seat in Zahle (from 6 to 10 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">An increase by 114 % in candidacy for the Maronite seat in West Bekaa and Rachaya (from 7 to 15 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">An increase by 662.5 % in candidacy for the two Maronite seats in Jezzine (from 8 to 13 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">An increase by 100 % in candidacy for the two Maronite seats in Saida (from 5 to 10 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">An increase by 100 % in candidacy for the two Shiite seats in Zahrani (from 4 to 8 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">An increase by 66 % in candidacy for the minorities seat in Beirut I (from 9 to 15 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">A decrease by 54 % in candidacy for the Orthodox seat in West Bekaa and Rachaya (from 11 to 5 candidates)</span></li><li><span style=\"background-color: transparent;\">A decrease by 57 % &amp; in candidacy for the Druze seat in Hasbaya - Marjeyoun (from 7 to 3 canA decrease by 55 % &amp; in candidacy for the Orthodox seat in Hasbaya - Marjeyoun (from 9 to 4 candidates)",
        "title": "Lebanon 2020 Elections: Candidates' Numbers & Confessions Analysis",
