        "description": "<p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Lately, Lebanese have been suffering from the idea of lifting subsidies on basic commodities, namely fuel. So what will happen to the transportation of the Lebanese state officials and employees?</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">It is remarkable that despite the many promises to adopt austerity policy in Lebanon, the estimated expenditures in the draft budget for the year 2020 is 143,459,308,000 LBP for liquid fuels, that is, approximately one hundred million dollars. It is noteworthy that the total amount has decreased compared to previous years so that the estimated cost was 201,818,64,000 LBP in 2018 and 156,016,475,000 LBP in 2019.</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">﻿</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">The estimated expenditures for fuel and energy (liquid fuel) were distributed based on the draft budget for the year 2020 according to these numbers:</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Lebanese Armed Forces: 82 billion LBP</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Internal Security Forces: 38 billion and 475 million LBP</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0); background-color: transparent;\">Lebanese General Security</span><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">: 13 billion and 650 million LBP</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">State Security: 5 billion and 250 million LBP</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">Lebanese Parliament: one billion and 800 million LBP</span></p><p><br></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">It is worthnoting that some basic ministries had been allocated a small amount, for example, the Ministry of Health, whose estimated expenditure of fuel was 92 million LBP, the Ministry of Social Affairs&nbsp;36 million LBP, and the Ministry of Justice 17 million LBP.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">It is worth mentioning&nbsp;that these numbers do not express the total fuel cost for state cars, where hundreds of vehicles and their costs should be added to it. These belong to 73 public institutions, more than 1000 municipalities and 56 federations of municipalities. This means that the cost may be doubled, thus leading to an increase in public expenditure.&nbsp;&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">This cost remains present as long as fuel is one of the commodities included in government support. Bringing down government deficits, it is expected that the consumption of liquid fuel by state institutions will reach more than one thousand billion LBP, or the situation will worsen, where the vehicles will be out of reach.&nbsp;</span></p><p><span style=\"color: rgb(0, 0, 0);\">In an attempt to limit spending and ensure the proper use of public money,&nbsp;isn't the state entitled to issue decrees that indicate precisely and clearly those entitled to use governmental cars? And to monitor these expenditures and behaviors? And uniting its public procurement by being the exclusive importer of fuel instead of devoting benefits and profits for the monopolists?</span></p>",
